<subSubSection id="2EFC65048939EF20FF41D03CAEB3F9A7" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="6659368F8939EF20FF41D03CAEB3F9A7" blockId="5.[192,1441,1570,1658]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis id="5492EA9D8939EF20FF41D03CAE53F9E7" bold="true" box="[192,324,1570,1594]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Remarks:</emphasis>
This sucking louse species is oligoxenous, infesting 
<taxonomicName id="A1E64D0C8939EF20FC4AD03CABD3F9E7" baseAuthorityName="Coues" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[971,1220,1570,1594]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Onychomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="torridus">
<emphasis id="5492EA9D8939EF20FC4AD03CABD3F9E7" box="[971,1220,1570,1594]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Onychomys torridus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the northern grasshopper mouse, 
<taxonomicName id="A1E64D0C8939EF20FE3ED05CAD7AF987" baseAuthorityName="Wied-Neuwied" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[447,621,1602,1626]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Onychomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucogaster">
<emphasis id="5492EA9D8939EF20FE3ED05CAD7AF987" box="[447,621,1602,1626]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">O. leucogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
throughout their ranges in the western 
<collectingCountry id="1EF1761F8939EF20FBE4D05CAB8DF987" box="[1125,1178,1602,1626]" name="United States of America" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">U.S.</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="1EF1761F8939EF20FB5BD05CAA27F987" box="[1242,1328,1602,1626]" name="Mexico" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="02774B7E8939EF20FAC3D05CAE8FF9A7" author="Durden, L. A. &amp; G. G. Musser" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" pagination="1 - 90" refId="ref9262" refString="Durden, L. A., and G. G. Musser. 1994. The sucking lice (Insecta, Anoplura) of the world: a checklist with records of mammalian hosts and geographical distributions. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 218: 1 - 90." type="journal article" year="1994">Durden and Musser 1994</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
